
Constants are compile-time declarations.
AST type-checks their initializers, folds what must fold and records facts for later stages.

Module constants are metadata.
They are not runtime top-level declaration statements.

## Main paths

- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/const_eval/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/module_ast/finalization/const_fact_collection.rs`
- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/module_ast/finalization/`

## Constant rules

Top-level `#` constants must:

- be initialised
- be immutable
- reference only compile-time values
- fully fold at compile time
- obey same-file source-order constant semantics
- obey cross-file dependency order from Stage 3

Runtime expressions in constants are rejected.

Header parsing records constant initializer reference hints so dependency sorting can order constants before AST folds them.
AST then performs semantic type checking and actual folding.

## Const facts

Const-fact collection runs after AST finalization.
It owns explicit module, private top-level and body-local const-fact collection.

Private inferred const facts are advisory metadata.
They can be projected into HIR for future optimisation consumers, but they don't change semantics in the current plan.
They don't participate in header dependency sorting and they don't become importable declarations.

## Const records

Struct instances assigned to constants can become data-only const records when all constructor arguments fold.

Const records are field-access-only compile-time member groups.
They can't be assigned to runtime values, passed, returned, placed in collections or used through runtime methods.

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    Defaults = |
        title String,
        year Int,
    |

    defaults #= Defaults("Beanstalk", 2026)

    page_title #= defaults.title
]

Const-record field projection is allowed when the expression fully folds.
That is why config-key constants can use values such as `Defaults().entry_root` after AST folding.

## Top-level const templates

Entry-file top-level const templates fold in AST into builder-facing compile-time fragments.
Each compile-time fragment records a runtime insertion index.
Builders merge those fragments into the runtime fragment list.

HIR doesn't carry compile-time page fragments.

Direct top-level const-template `if` and `loop` forms like those below must
fully fold at compile time.

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    #[if show:
        Visible
    ]

    #[loop items |item|:
        [item]
    ]
]

Const-required `if` validates every branch body.
Const conditional loops fold to no-output only when the condition is compile-time `false`.
Compile-time `true` and runtime/unknown conditions are rejected for conditional loops.

Const range/collection loops use `template_const_loop_iteration_limit`.
The default is `10_000` and the cap is `1_000_000`.

## Folding and numeric semantics

Compile-time folding should agree with runtime lowering.

Examples:

- statically known numeric failures are compile-time diagnostics
- `String -> Int` and `Float -> Int` casts enforce the signed 32-bit range
- `String -> Float` rejects grammar-valid text that materialises to non-finite `Float`
- `Float -> String` uses Beanstalk's formatter, not backend-native display
- runtime Float interpolation and compile-time template folding use the same formatting rules

If compile-time and runtime formatting differ, templates become target-dependent.
Avoid that.

## Config extraction

`config.bst` is compiled through the frontend up to AST.
Stage 0 extracts only authored known top-level config-key constants declared with `name #= value`
or `name #Type = value` from shared AST const facts.
Imported constants and support declarations may help config expressions, but they never become config entries.

This lets config use the same folding and diagnostics as source constants without making config a runtime module.

## Common mistakes

- Treating constants as runtime top-level statements.
- Letting HIR decide whether a constant folds.
- Letting private inferred const facts change semantics.
- Carrying compile-time page fragments through HIR.
- Allowing runtime expressions in const initializers.
- Forgetting same-file constant source-order semantics.
- Letting compile-time and runtime Float formatting drift.

